those of you that are pure
carnivore for whatever reason,

1031
00:37:11,910 --> 00:37:14,040
and those of you that are
omnivores for whatever reason.

1032
00:37:14,040 --> 00:37:15,390
I happen to be an omnivore.

1033
00:37:15,390 --> 00:37:17,250
My goal is always to eat high quality,

1034
00:37:17,250 --> 00:37:19,140
minimally or non-processed foods

1035
00:37:19,140 --> 00:37:20,400
and to eat things in moderation.

1036
00:37:20,400 --> 00:37:21,960
So I do eat some meat

1037
00:37:21,960 --> 00:37:24,720
from sustainable sources
or from organic sources,

1038
00:37:24,720 --> 00:37:27,900
I eat some starches and I eat
vegetables and I eat fruits,

1039
00:37:27,900 --> 00:37:29,220
I try not to eat sugars

1040
00:37:29,220 --> 00:37:30,780
and I don't really like
highly processed foods

1041
00:37:30,780 --> 00:37:31,800
at this point in my life.

1042
00:37:31,800 --> 00:37:33,000
That's me, that's what I do,

1043
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:35,340
but I'm certainly not dictating
what people should eat.

1044
00:37:35,340 --> 00:37:36,960
I know certain people are ketogenic,

1045
00:37:36,960 --> 00:37:40,050
and I can say that for
people who achieve ketosis

1046
00:37:40,050 --> 00:37:41,280
and can get into ketosis,

1047
00:37:41,280 --> 00:37:44,820
yes indeed, there is a mental
state associated with ketosis

1048
00:37:44,820 --> 00:37:46,770
that will allow your brain to function

1049
00:37:46,770 --> 00:37:48,060
and to think really clearly

1050
00:37:48,060 --> 00:37:49,860
that many people find very attractive

1051
00:37:49,860 --> 00:37:52,140
and keep them going
back over and over again

1052
00:37:52,140 --> 00:37:53,430
to a ketogenic diet.

1053
00:37:53,430 --> 00:37:56,130
I'm somebody who for instance
has not been in ketosis

1054
00:37:56,130 --> 00:37:57,030
many times in my life,

1055
00:37:57,030 --> 00:37:58,680
at least not deliberately so,

1056
00:37:58,680 --> 00:38:01,350
but I actually will ingest
liquid ketones from time to time

1057
00:38:01,350 --> 00:38:03,690
because of the further
cognitive enhancement

1058
00:38:03,690 --> 00:38:05,310
and physical enhancement that I experience

1059
00:38:05,310 --> 00:38:08,730
on top of nutrition that does
include some carbohydrates.

1060
00:38:08,730 --> 00:38:11,100
So there are a lot of different
ways to approach all this,

1061
00:38:11,100 --> 00:38:12,810
whether or not you're a vegan, omnivore,

1062
00:38:12,810 --> 00:38:16,171
vegetarian, carnivore, et
cetera, the point is this,

1063
00:38:16,171 --> 00:38:17,760
your ability to focus,

1064
00:38:17,760 --> 00:38:19,650
and in fact, your ability of neurons

1065
00:38:19,650 --> 00:38:22,470
to encode specific information
in your environment,

1066
00:38:22,470 --> 00:38:25,140
that is to represent what's
out there in the world,

1067
00:38:25,140 --> 00:38:28,080
is actually related to
your blood glucose level.

1068
00:38:28,080 --> 00:38:30,720
Now here I'm setting aside the discussion

1069
00:38:30,720 --> 00:38:33,870
of ketosis and ketogenic
diets for the moment,

1070
00:38:33,870 --> 00:38:34,890
but there's a beautiful study

1071
00:38:34,890 --> 00:38:36,450
that was published in Neuron not long ago

1072
00:38:36,450 --> 00:38:37,500
that showed that the tuning,

1073
00:38:37,500 --> 00:38:40,350
that is the precision with
which neurons in the brain

1074
00:38:40,350 --> 00:38:42,390
will represent things in our environment

1075
00:38:42,390 --> 00:38:44,730
is actually much greater

1076
00:38:44,730 --> 00:38:47,040
when there is sufficient
glucose in the brain.

1077
00:38:47,040 --> 00:38:50,070
Translated into English, this
means that when we are fasted

1078
00:38:50,070 --> 00:38:52,020
or when our blood glucose is very low,

1079
00:38:52,020 --> 00:38:54,840
we aren't able to perceive
and think about things

1080
00:38:54,840 --> 00:38:56,040
as clearly.

1081
00:38:56,040 --> 00:38:57,720
Now there's a twist to this, however.

1082
00:38:57,720 --> 00:38:59,820
Many people who practice
intermittent fasting,

1083
00:38:59,820 --> 00:39:00,653
and I should say

1084
00:39:00,653 --> 00:39:02,430
I practice a sort of pseudo
intermittent fasting,

1085
00:39:02,430 --> 00:39:03,630
I generally eat my meals

1086
00:39:03,630 --> 00:39:05,850
between the hours of 11:00 AM and 8:00 PM

1087
00:39:05,850 --> 00:39:07,890
although sometimes there's
some wiggle around that,

1088
00:39:07,890 --> 00:39:09,270
occasionally have an early breakfast,

1089
00:39:09,270 --> 00:39:10,710
I'm not super rigid about it,

1090
00:39:10,710 --> 00:39:12,030
but I know there are a number of people

1091
00:39:12,030 --> 00:39:13,260
who are doing longer fasts

1092
00:39:13,260 --> 00:39:15,108
or they're eating in a six hour window.

1093
00:39:15,108 --> 00:39:17,850
We did an entire episode about fasting,

1094
00:39:17,850 --> 00:39:19,980
you can again find that
at hubermanlab.com,

1095
00:39:19,980 --> 00:39:21,750
we'll likely have Satchin Panda,

1096
00:39:21,750 --> 00:39:24,810
who's an expert in intermittent
fasting, on the podcast.

1097
00:39:24,810 --> 00:39:26,250
Intermittent fasting

1098
00:39:26,250 --> 00:39:28,608
has a lot of different potential benefits.

1099
00:39:28,608 --> 00:39:29,610
For some people,

1100
00:39:29,610 --> 00:39:31,470
it's a convenient way to
restrict their calories.

1101
00:39:31,470 --> 00:39:33,660
For other people, it's a
convenient way to avoid eating,

1102
00:39:33,660 --> 00:39:36,300
that is it's easier to not eat
than to eat a small portion

1103
00:39:36,300 --> 00:39:39,870
so they opt for intermittent
fasting and so on and so forth.

1104
00:39:39,870 --> 00:39:41,730
But one of the things
that you hear very often

1105
00:39:41,730 --> 00:39:43,440
is that some people like being fasted

1106
00:39:43,440 --> 00:39:46,740
because they like the clarity
of mind that it provides.

1107
00:39:46,740 --> 00:39:48,060
Here's the situation.

1108
00:39:48,060 --> 00:39:50,010
Neurons, unless you're
in a ketogenic diet,

1109
00:39:50,010 --> 00:39:53,130
really thrive on glucose,
they love glucose.

1110
00:39:53,130 --> 00:39:54,690
And as I mentioned before,

1111
00:39:54,690 --> 00:39:56,520
your ability to think and perceive things

1112
00:39:56,520 --> 00:39:57,870
is actually enhanced

1113
00:39:57,870 --> 00:40:00,060
by having sufficient
glucose in your bloodstream.

1114
00:40:00,060 --> 00:40:02,460
So why would it be that
some people experience

1115
00:40:02,460 --> 00:40:05,100
a heightened state of mental
clarity when they are fasted?

1116
00:40:05,100 --> 00:40:06,572
I've certainly experienced that before.

1117
00:40:06,572 --> 00:40:07,500
Well, I should say

1118
00:40:07,500 --> 00:40:09,540
that provided you're well hydrated enough

1119
00:40:09,540 --> 00:40:11,490
and you have enough
electrolytes in your system,

1120
00:40:11,490 --> 00:40:14,130
what tends to happen is
that when you ingest food,

1121
00:40:14,130 --> 00:40:15,660
there's a shift in your nervous system

1122
00:40:15,660 --> 00:40:17,700
towards so-called parasympathetic mode,

1123
00:40:17,700 --> 00:40:19,200
that is the more relaxed,

1124
00:40:19,200 --> 00:40:20,790
you've probably heard
it as rest and digest,

1125
00:40:20,790 --> 00:40:21,623
although it does other things,

1126
00:40:21,623 --> 00:40:24,540
the more relaxed mode that can
indeed make us very sleepy.

1127
00:40:24,540 --> 00:40:25,830
If we have too many carbohydrates,

1128
00:40:25,830 --> 00:40:27,450
it actually can make us quite sleepy.

1129
00:40:27,450 --> 00:40:29,730
However, if we have any food,

1130
00:40:29,730 --> 00:40:31,140
if we have enough of it,

1131
00:40:31,140 --> 00:40:32,760
that is if our gut is full,

1132
00:40:32,760 --> 00:40:34,050
it diverts blood to our gut

1133
00:40:34,050 --> 00:40:36,450
and we become sleepy and
we can't focus as well.

1134
00:40:36,450 --> 00:40:38,400
So a lot of people really like fasting

1135
00:40:38,400 --> 00:40:41,700
and the state of being fasted
for focus and concentration

1136
00:40:41,700 --> 00:40:43,980
because they don't have as much

1137
00:40:43,980 --> 00:40:45,930
of that parasympathetic activation,

1138
00:40:45,930 --> 00:40:46,950
they're just not as sleepy.

1139
00:40:46,950 --> 00:40:48,570
And in fact, under those conditions,

1140
00:40:48,570 --> 00:40:51,330
half as much caffeine will
give you just as much lift

1141
00:40:51,330 --> 00:40:53,490
as twice as much caffeine will give you

1142
00:40:53,490 --> 00:40:54,720
on a full belly of pasta

1143
00:40:54,720 --> 00:40:56,520
and that's just the way
that caffeine interacts

1144
00:40:56,520 --> 00:40:57,360
with blood glucose.

1145
00:40:57,360 --> 00:40:58,920
So what I'd like you to imagine

1146
00:40:58,920 --> 00:41:02,310
is if you had a measure
of focus from zero to 10,

1147
00:41:02,310 --> 00:41:03,420
these are arbitrary units,

1148
00:41:03,420 --> 00:41:04,800
10 being maximally focused

1149
00:41:04,800 --> 00:41:06,960
and zero being not focused at all,

1150
00:41:06,960 --> 00:41:10,020
imagine a U-shaped function, right,

1151
00:41:10,020 --> 00:41:11,850
where if you're very fasted,

1152
00:41:11,850 --> 00:41:14,850
you're going to have high degree
of focus and concentration,

1153
00:41:14,850 --> 00:41:17,340
but then if you ingest some
food and your belly is full,

1154
00:41:17,340 --> 00:41:19,680
your focus and concentration is reduced.

1155
00:41:19,680 --> 00:41:21,916
But having enough blood glucose

1156
00:41:21,916 --> 00:41:24,360
and maybe even elevated blood glucose

1157
00:41:24,360 --> 00:41:25,830
will increase cognitive function.

1158
00:41:25,830 --> 00:41:27,060
So there are two ends of the spectrum.

1159
00:41:27,060 --> 00:41:28,320
On one end of the spectrum,

1160
00:41:28,320 --> 00:41:31,140
blood glucose is relatively
low and you're fasted

1161
00:41:31,140 --> 00:41:34,680
and you can think and behave
in a very concentrated way

1162
00:41:34,680 --> 00:41:36,300
and on the other end of the spectrum,

1163
00:41:36,300 --> 00:41:38,160
you have a lot of blood
glucose, or I should say,

1164
00:41:38,160 --> 00:41:39,150
sufficient blood glucose,

1165
00:41:39,150 --> 00:41:41,460
you never want your blood
glucose to be too high,

1166
00:41:41,460 --> 00:41:45,210
and that allows your neurons
to encode and perceive

1167
00:41:45,210 --> 00:41:47,430
and basically allow you
to think really clearly.

1168
00:41:47,430 --> 00:41:49,500
So you sort of have to
pick your condition.

1169
00:41:49,500 --> 00:41:52,800
What do you want for your bouts
of focus and concentration?

1170
00:41:52,800 --> 00:41:53,820
I actually do both.

1171
00:41:53,820 --> 00:41:55,350
So what I do is, as I mentioned before,

1172
00:41:55,350 --> 00:41:57,330
I eat my meal sometime around 11:00 AM,

1173
00:41:57,330 --> 00:41:58,470
my first meal typically

1174
00:41:58,470 --> 00:42:00,060
unless I'm very hungry when I wake up.

1175
00:42:00,060 --> 00:42:04,600
And so I will do my workout
and one about of focused work.

1176
00:42:04,600 --> 00:42:07,530
I always think of this as my
hard work early in the day

1177
00:42:07,530 --> 00:42:08,940
and I do that fasted,

1178
00:42:08,940 --> 00:42:11,220
I'll be consuming water with electrolytes,

1179
00:42:11,220 --> 00:42:12,660
maybe LMNT or other electrolytes,

1180
00:42:12,660 --> 00:42:15,960
maybe some caffeine as well
in the form of yerba mate

1181
00:42:15,960 --> 00:42:20,340
or coffee, that's my first focus
about of 90 minutes or less,

1182
00:42:20,340 --> 00:42:22,860
that is essentially done
fasted and then I'll eat

1183
00:42:22,860 --> 00:42:24,720
and then I do notice after I eat,

1184
00:42:24,720 --> 00:42:26,880
I actually have a diminished
capacity to focus.

1185
00:42:26,880 --> 00:42:28,230
But then again in the afternoon,

1186
00:42:28,230 --> 00:42:30,180
I will do another 90
minute about of focus,

1187
00:42:30,180 --> 00:42:31,710
and I'll talk about
some of the tools I use

1188
00:42:31,710 --> 00:42:34,110
to make sure that that
about of focus is optimal

1189
00:42:34,110 --> 00:42:37,440
for getting the most amount
of focused work done,

1190
00:42:37,440 --> 00:42:39,330
whether or not it's mental
work or physical work,

1191
00:42:39,330 --> 00:42:41,337
although I tend to do my
physical work early in the day

1192
00:42:41,337 --> 00:42:44,550
and my mental work both
early and late in the day.

1193
00:42:44,550 --> 00:42:48,330
So to make this very simple
or as simple as I can for you

1194
00:42:48,330 --> 00:42:52,050
being fasted is great for
focus and concentration

1195
00:42:52,050 --> 00:42:55,140
provided you're not thinking
about food the entire time

1196
00:42:55,140 --> 00:42:58,040
and being fed is terrific
for focus and concentration,

1197
00:42:58,040 --> 00:43:00,540
it actually can improve neuronal function

1198
00:43:00,540 --> 00:43:02,970
provided that you didn't
eat too much food.

1199
00:43:02,970 --> 00:43:04,980
So one way to manage this

1200
00:43:04,980 --> 00:43:06,240
is if you're going to have a lunch,

1201
00:43:06,240 --> 00:43:08,370
to make sure that you don't
stuff yourself at lunch,

1202
00:43:08,370 --> 00:43:11,730
that you're not overeating
and to not get quite so full

1203
00:43:11,730 --> 00:43:13,680
that you put your nervous system

1204
00:43:13,680 --> 00:43:15,180
into this parasympathetic mode

1205
00:43:15,180 --> 00:43:17,250
and make it hard to
focus in the afternoon.

1206
00:43:17,250 --> 00:43:18,600
I know a lot of people experience a dip

1207
00:43:18,600 --> 00:43:20,340
or even a crash in energy in the afternoon

1208
00:43:20,340 --> 00:43:21,900
that make it really hard to focus.

1209
00:43:21,900 --> 00:43:23,360
For that reason, I'll just remind people

1210
00:43:23,360 --> 00:43:25,282
of a tool I've talked
about many times before,

1211
00:43:25,282 --> 00:43:26,760
which is based on the biology

1212
00:43:26,760 --> 00:43:28,590
of adenosine and caffeine, et cetera,

1213
00:43:28,590 --> 00:43:31,110
which is to delay your
first caffeine intake

1214
00:43:31,110 --> 00:43:33,660
to 90 to 120 minutes after waking up.

1215
00:43:33,660 --> 00:43:35,386
I know that can be painful
for certain people.

1216
00:43:35,386 --> 00:43:36,870
I violate that rule,

1217
00:43:36,870 --> 00:43:38,790
when I'm working out very
early in the morning.

1218
00:43:38,790 --> 00:43:40,922
I'll drink my caffeine before my workout

1219
00:43:40,922 --> 00:43:45,210
which often occurs within
30 to 60 minutes of waking.

1220
00:43:45,210 --> 00:43:47,940
But in general, unless I'm
working out very early,

1221
00:43:47,940 --> 00:43:52,500
I will ingest my caffeine 90
to 120 minutes after I wake up.

1222
00:43:52,500 --> 00:43:53,880
So again, I want to emphasize

1223
00:43:53,880 --> 00:43:56,160
that if you hear somebody out there say

1224
00:43:56,160 --> 00:43:59,640
being fasted is optimal for
focus and concentration.

1225
00:43:59,640 --> 00:44:02,220
Well, that is true in one context

1226
00:44:02,220 --> 00:44:04,800
and perhaps ideal for a
certain part of the day.

1227
00:44:04,800 --> 00:44:07,980
And other people will say,
no, neurons run on glucose,

1228
00:44:07,980 --> 00:44:09,870
you need glucose in your bloodstream

1229
00:44:09,870 --> 00:44:12,390
in order to get those neurons to be tuned,

1230
00:44:12,390 --> 00:44:14,520
that is to respond with
electrical activity

1231
00:44:14,520 --> 00:44:16,950
in the optimal way when
you're reading something

1232
00:44:16,950 --> 00:44:18,210
or when you're trying to perform exercise.

1233
00:44:18,210 --> 00:44:19,290
Well, that's also true.

1234
00:44:19,290 --> 00:44:21,330
And of course, you can incorporate both.

1235
00:44:21,330 --> 00:44:23,790
I, in fact as I just described,

1236
00:44:23,790 --> 00:44:27,090
incorporate both fasted
states and fed states

1237
00:44:27,090 --> 00:44:30,063
in order to optimize my
concentration and focus.

1238
00:44:30,930 --> 00:44:33,210
And as a brief note about ketosis,

1239
00:44:33,210 --> 00:44:34,770
for those of you that actually managed

1240
00:44:34,770 --> 00:44:36,210
to transition into ketosis

1241
00:44:36,210 --> 00:44:38,640
and are maintaining a ketogenic state,

1242
00:44:38,640 --> 00:44:40,680
that, as I mentioned earlier,

1243
00:44:40,680 --> 00:44:44,850
can enhance brain function,
concentration and focus

1244
00:44:44,850 --> 00:44:47,460
because of the way in
which ketones can be used

1245
00:44:47,460 --> 00:44:50,850
as a so-called optimal fuel for neurons.

1246
00:44:50,850 --> 00:44:54,210
The ketogenic diet was
originally designed, if you will,

1247
00:44:54,210 --> 00:44:55,470
for epilepsy,

1248
00:44:55,470 --> 00:44:57,000
it has a whole relationship to epilepsy

1249
00:44:57,000 --> 00:44:58,710
and controlling epileptic seizures,

1250
00:44:58,710 --> 00:45:00,990
and it can in fact allow people

1251
00:45:00,990 --> 00:45:03,330
to achieve focus,
concentrated brain states.

1252
00:45:03,330 --> 00:45:05,370
So in the future, I'll do
an episode about ketosis

1253
00:45:05,370 --> 00:45:07,590
and be sure to circle back
on how to optimize ketosis

1254
00:45:07,590 --> 00:45:08,790
for focus and concentration.

1255
00:45:08,790 --> 00:45:09,780
Although I have to believe

1256
00:45:09,780 --> 00:45:11,130
that most of the people listening to this

1257
00:45:11,130 --> 00:45:14,040
are probably not in ketosis
or following a ketogenic diet

1258
00:45:14,040 --> 00:45:15,210
so that's why I mainly focused

1259
00:45:15,210 --> 00:45:18,870
on fasted states and fed states.

1260
00:45:18,870 --> 00:45:20,730
And just to make sure that I'm thorough,

1261
00:45:20,730 --> 00:45:22,050
a fasted state to me

1262
00:45:22,050 --> 00:45:25,230
would be a state in which you
haven't ingested any calories,

1263
00:45:25,230 --> 00:45:27,090
but may have ingested caffeine

1264
00:45:27,090 --> 00:45:29,160
or maybe even a small amount
of artificial sweetener

1265
00:45:29,160 --> 00:45:30,510
or something like that,

1266
00:45:30,510 --> 00:45:31,950
but really haven't ingested

1267
00:45:31,950 --> 00:45:33,690
any significant number of calories

1268
00:45:33,690 --> 00:45:36,870
in the previous four to
eight or maybe even 12 hours.

1269
00:45:36,870 --> 00:45:38,700
And again, there's
tremendous variation here,

1270
00:45:38,700 --> 00:45:40,410
depending on how long people have fasted,

1271
00:45:40,410 --> 00:45:41,670
whether or not we're
talking about the state

1272
00:45:41,670 --> 00:45:43,410
right after people wake up, et cetera.

1273
00:45:43,410 --> 00:45:45,150
Again, if you're interested
in intermittent fasting,

1274
00:45:45,150 --> 00:45:46,530
both for the sake of mental

1275
00:45:46,530 --> 00:45:48,660
and physical health and performance,

1276
00:45:48,660 --> 00:45:51,240
check out our episode on
fasting at hubermanlab.com.

1277
00:45:51,240 --> 00:45:53,160
I also want to touch back on this idea

1278
00:45:53,160 --> 00:45:55,482
of which foods can increase focus.

1279
00:45:55,482 --> 00:45:58,410
You know, in the episode
on ADHD that I did,

1280
00:45:58,410 --> 00:46:00,390
I touched on this quite a bit

1281
00:46:00,390 --> 00:46:02,340
as it relates to elimination diets.

1282
00:46:02,340 --> 00:46:04,200
There's a whole industry

1283
00:46:04,200 --> 00:46:06,510
and a ton of interest for obvious reasons

1284
00:46:06,510 --> 00:46:08,970
into what sorts of things kids and adults

1285
00:46:08,970 --> 00:46:09,900
should and shouldn't eat

1286
00:46:09,900 --> 00:46:12,030
in order to reduce symptoms of ADHD.

1287
00:46:12,030 --> 00:46:15,660
I think that the sum total of
those data point to the fact

1288
00:46:15,660 --> 00:46:17,310
that reducing simple sugar intake

1289
00:46:17,310 --> 00:46:19,320
and certainly highly processed foods,

1290
00:46:19,320 --> 00:46:22,020
so ice cream, candy, chips, et cetera,

1291
00:46:22,020 --> 00:46:22,853
those sorts of things,

1292
00:46:22,853 --> 00:46:25,170
really does seem to
improve symptoms of ADHD

1293
00:46:25,170 --> 00:46:26,940
in both children and adults.

1294
00:46:26,940 --> 00:46:28,950
But once you move past
that and you start to say,

1295
00:46:28,950 --> 00:46:31,830
well, which foods can improve
concentration and focus?

1296
00:46:31,830 --> 00:46:35,400
Well, foods that for instance
include a lot of tyrosine,

1297
00:46:35,400 --> 00:46:36,870
which is a precursor to dopamine,

1298
00:46:36,870 --> 00:46:40,170
and now you know why dopamine
is important in this context,

1299
00:46:40,170 --> 00:46:42,720
are certainly going to increase
concentration and focus.

1300
00:46:42,720 --> 00:46:44,790
So things like Parmesan cheese,

1301
00:46:44,790 --> 00:46:46,020
certain meats, certain nuts,

1302
00:46:46,020 --> 00:46:47,460
you can look up which foods

1303
00:46:47,460 --> 00:46:48,930
contain high amounts of tyrosine.

1304
00:46:48,930 --> 00:46:50,700
There are also some fruits and vegetables

1305
00:46:50,700 --> 00:46:52,620
that include high amounts of tyrosine,

1306
00:46:52,620 --> 00:46:55,260
but to be quite direct,

1307
00:46:55,260 --> 00:46:59,130
it doesn't matter whether or
not you're ingesting foods

1308
00:46:59,130 --> 00:47:01,740
that are rich in the precursor amino acids

1309
00:47:01,740 --> 00:47:04,020
to dopamine, acetylcholine, et cetera,

1310
00:47:04,020 --> 00:47:07,020
if you are consuming large
amounts of those foods.

1311
00:47:07,020 --> 00:47:09,960
That is one can look and see for instance,

1312
00:47:09,960 --> 00:47:13,470
that a steak includes
a lot of the precursors

1313
00:47:13,470 --> 00:47:14,730
to acetylcholine.

1314
00:47:14,730 --> 00:47:17,640
It has amino acid precursors
to dopamine as well

1315
00:47:17,640 --> 00:47:19,530
and there are other foods
that will do that as well,

1316
00:47:19,530 --> 00:47:22,560
but if I were to ingest
say two ribeye steaks,

1317
00:47:22,560 --> 00:47:24,030
that's a lot of meat

1318
00:47:24,030 --> 00:47:26,850
and it will direct a
lot of blood to my gut

1319
00:47:26,850 --> 00:47:29,130
and it will cause me to be sleepy

1320
00:47:29,130 --> 00:47:31,140
and that will create challenges of me

1321
00:47:31,140 --> 00:47:33,990
being able to achieve states
of focus and concentration.

1322
00:47:33,990 --> 00:47:36,570
So the simple way to put
this is if you eat too much

1323
00:47:36,570 --> 00:47:38,670
or you eat a very large volume of food,

1324
00:47:38,670 --> 00:47:42,690
you are going to diminish
your focus and concentration.

1325
00:47:42,690 --> 00:47:44,040
The key is to eat enough

1326
00:47:44,040 --> 00:47:46,560
that you're nourished for
the certain activities,

1327
00:47:46,560 --> 00:47:48,930
mental and physical that
you need to perform,

1328
00:47:48,930 --> 00:47:50,520
but if you're eating large meals,

1329
00:47:50,520 --> 00:47:53,700
you are going to diminish
your concentration and focus

1330
00:47:53,700 --> 00:47:54,533
period.

1331
00:47:54,533 --> 00:47:57,150
I know many people are curious
as to whether or not caffeine

1332
00:47:57,150 --> 00:48:01,710
can improve focus and
concentration, and indeed it can.

1333
00:48:01,710 --> 00:48:04,980
There is an immense amount
of data supporting the idea

1334
00:48:04,980 --> 00:48:05,814
that caffeine,

1335
00:48:05,814 --> 00:48:08,250
provided its consumed in
the appropriate dosages,

1336
00:48:08,250 --> 00:48:11,160
can improve mental performance
and physical performance,

1337
00:48:11,160 --> 00:48:12,960
and it largely does that

1338
00:48:12,960 --> 00:48:16,388
through improvements in
focus and concentration.

1339
00:48:16,388 --> 00:48:18,570
The dosage of caffeine of course,

1340
00:48:18,570 --> 00:48:21,300
is going to depend on how
caffeine adapted you are,

1341
00:48:21,300 --> 00:48:23,490
how much caffeine tolerance you have.

1342
00:48:23,490 --> 00:48:25,795
And that is going to vary tremendously

1343
00:48:25,795 --> 00:48:28,920
depending on whether or not
you ingest that caffeine

1344
00:48:28,920 --> 00:48:31,410
with or without food,
as I mentioned earlier.

1345
00:48:31,410 --> 00:48:33,600
But there is a kind of general range

1346
00:48:33,600 --> 00:48:35,610
in which we can talk about caffeine

1347
00:48:35,610 --> 00:48:37,830
as being useful for
focus and concentration.

1348
00:48:37,830 --> 00:48:39,690
And the range is basically

1349
00:48:39,690 --> 00:48:42,330
from 100 milligrams to 400 milligrams.

1350
00:48:42,330 --> 00:48:44,040
I want to caution everybody out there,

1351
00:48:44,040 --> 00:48:46,470
if you're somebody who
suffers from anxiety

1352
00:48:46,470 --> 00:48:47,700
or panic attacks,

1353
00:48:47,700 --> 00:48:49,380
and you're not used to ingesting caffeine

1354
00:48:49,380 --> 00:48:51,920
and you run out and ingest
400 milligrams of caffeine

1355
00:48:51,920 --> 00:48:53,970
in the form of espresso or yerba mate

1356
00:48:53,970 --> 00:48:56,400
or an energy drink or in pill form,

1357
00:48:56,400 --> 00:48:58,410
that is going to be very
uncomfortable for you,

1358
00:48:58,410 --> 00:48:59,880
you're going to be sweating profusely,

1359
00:48:59,880 --> 00:49:01,140
your heart rate is going to increase,

1360
00:49:01,140 --> 00:49:04,080
you're going to be quite panicked in fact

1361
00:49:04,080 --> 00:49:05,460
or at least anxious.

1362
00:49:05,460 --> 00:49:09,210
So be cautious with your
use and adopting of caffeine

1363
00:49:09,210 --> 00:49:11,460
if you're not already caffeine adapted,

1364
00:49:11,460 --> 00:49:12,780
but most people do quite well

1365
00:49:12,780 --> 00:49:15,450
to ingest 100 to 200
milligrams of caffeine

1366
00:49:15,450 --> 00:49:17,640
prior to doing some focused work.

1367
00:49:17,640 --> 00:49:20,310
And again, I recommend
delaying your caffeine intake

1368
00:49:20,310 --> 00:49:22,470
to 90 to 120 minutes after waking,

1369
00:49:22,470 --> 00:49:24,330
unless you're using that caffeine

1370
00:49:24,330 --> 00:49:28,170
to really jolt your
system before a workout.

1371
00:49:28,170 --> 00:49:31,020
Caffeine can of course be
ingested in various forms,

1372
00:49:31,020 --> 00:49:32,040
even pill form,

1373
00:49:32,040 --> 00:49:33,870
but most people ingest
it in the form of coffee

1374
00:49:33,870 --> 00:49:36,480
or my particular favorite
way to ingest caffeine

1375
00:49:36,480 --> 00:49:37,890
is yerba mate.

1376
00:49:37,890 --> 00:49:40,050
It is important and I should note

1377
00:49:40,050 --> 00:49:42,360
that you should actively avoid

1378
00:49:42,360 --> 00:49:44,010
the smoked versions of yerba mate

1379
00:49:44,010 --> 00:49:45,780
as they contain a lot of carcinogenic,

1380
00:49:45,780 --> 00:49:47,400
cancer promoting compounds.

1381
00:49:47,400 --> 00:49:49,887
There's some great yerba
mate brands out there.

1382
00:49:49,887 --> 00:49:52,470
The most cost effective way to consume it

1383
00:49:52,470 --> 00:49:53,850
would be to use the loose leaf tea

1384
00:49:53,850 --> 00:49:55,641
and to pour water over that.

1385
00:49:55,641 --> 00:49:57,660
There's one particular brand that I like,

1386
00:49:57,660 --> 00:50:00,090
I don't have any affiliation
to them whatsoever,

1387
00:50:00,090 --> 00:50:02,040
but I've been using it
for years, it's Anna Park.

1388
00:50:02,040 --> 00:50:05,490
It's an organic brand that is
sold, I buy mine on Amazon,

1389
00:50:05,490 --> 00:50:07,380
you can find it elsewhere
on the internet as well.

1390
00:50:07,380 --> 00:50:09,030
Again, I don't have any
affiliation to them,

1391
00:50:09,030 --> 00:50:10,710
it's just very cost effective, very clean,

1392
00:50:10,710 --> 00:50:12,570
it doesn't have the smoked flavor,

1393
00:50:12,570 --> 00:50:14,490
at least the one that I buy
is not the smoked variety

1394
00:50:14,490 --> 00:50:16,860
so none of the carcinogenic
compounds are in there

1395
00:50:16,860 --> 00:50:20,190
at least that I'm aware of
and I like the way it tastes

1396
00:50:20,190 --> 00:50:23,530
and it provides a very
even lift and stimulant

1397
00:50:23,530 --> 00:50:25,620
that I think certainly works for me

1398
00:50:25,620 --> 00:50:26,597
and that a number of people I know

1399
00:50:26,597 --> 00:50:29,430
that I have suggested to also enjoy.

1400
00:50:29,430 --> 00:50:34,320
Yerba mate or caffeine also
have other additional benefits,

1401
00:50:34,320 --> 00:50:38,010
in particular, the caffeine
in yerba mate and coffee

1402
00:50:38,010 --> 00:50:39,120
and other sources of caffeine

1403
00:50:39,120 --> 00:50:42,300
are known to increase
the density and efficacy,

1404
00:50:42,300 --> 00:50:46,710
that is the number and the
function of dopamine receptors,

1405
00:50:46,710 --> 00:50:49,350
and this has been shown
in humans several times.

1406
00:50:49,350 --> 00:50:51,300
So by ingesting caffeine pretty regularly,

1407
00:50:51,300 --> 00:50:53,610
you're actually increasing
the ability of dopamine

1408
00:50:53,610 --> 00:50:57,930
to have this effect of
increasing motivation and drive.

1409
00:50:57,930 --> 00:51:00,390
I tend to ingest caffeine
only early in the day,

1410
00:51:00,390 --> 00:51:01,980
I tend to cut off my caffeine intake

1411
00:51:01,980 --> 00:51:03,660
somewhere around one or 2:00 PM

1412
00:51:03,660 --> 00:51:05,820
to ensure that I can get
into a good night's sleep,

1413
00:51:05,820 --> 00:51:07,230
but I realize that there
are people out there

1414
00:51:07,230 --> 00:51:08,130
that ingest caffeine

1415
00:51:08,130 --> 00:51:09,930
as late as two or three in the afternoon

1416
00:51:09,930 --> 00:51:11,340
and can still sleep fine.

1417
00:51:11,340 --> 00:51:12,570
I will caution those of you

1418
00:51:12,570 --> 00:51:13,920
that think that you can drink caffeine

1419
00:51:13,920 --> 00:51:16,063
in the evening or nighttime
and still fall asleep.

1420
00:51:16,063 --> 00:51:18,540
All of the research points to the fact

1421
00:51:18,540 --> 00:51:20,010
that the architecture of your sleep

1422
00:51:20,010 --> 00:51:21,660
and the depth of your sleep is disrupted.

1423
00:51:21,660 --> 00:51:24,330
Even if you're able to
fall and stay asleep,

1424
00:51:24,330 --> 00:51:26,010
the sleep you're getting
is simply not as good

1425
00:51:26,010 --> 00:51:26,880
as the sleep you would get

1426
00:51:26,880 --> 00:51:29,191
if you were to shut off
your caffeine intake

1427
00:51:29,191 --> 00:51:31,230
at least eight hours before bedtime,

1428
00:51:31,230 --> 00:51:33,960
and ideally more like 10 or
even 12 hours before bedtime.

1429
00:51:33,960 --> 00:51:36,780
But of course, there are
practical constraints as well.

1430
00:51:36,780 --> 00:51:41,010
Okay so caffeine is
increasing dopamine's function

1431
00:51:41,010 --> 00:51:44,939
by changing the number and
efficacy of dopamine receptors,

1432
00:51:44,939 --> 00:51:47,130
but of course, it also
increases our wakefulness,

1433
00:51:47,130 --> 00:51:48,270
our alertness,

1434
00:51:48,270 --> 00:51:51,210
and that is largely through
the neurochemical systems

1435
00:51:51,210 --> 00:51:52,530
related to adenosine,

1436
00:51:52,530 --> 00:51:54,660
which is a molecule that
builds up in our brain and body

1437
00:51:54,660 --> 00:51:55,710
the longer we are awake,

1438
00:51:55,710 --> 00:51:58,560
it's part of the sleepiness
system if you will,

1439
00:51:58,560 --> 00:52:00,780
it makes us feel fatigued or tired,

1440
00:52:00,780 --> 00:52:05,160
and caffeine also operates
on the epinephrine,

1441
00:52:05,160 --> 00:52:06,480
the adrenaline system.

1442
00:52:06,480 --> 00:52:08,070
In fact, if we ingest too much caffeine,

1443
00:52:08,070 --> 00:52:09,840
we'll sometimes get the jitters.

1444
00:52:09,840 --> 00:52:13,410
Those jitters are really the
sympathetic, as it's called,

1445
00:52:13,410 --> 00:52:15,750
nervous system's bias toward movement,

1446
00:52:15,750 --> 00:52:19,470
and our pupils will dilate,
they actually get broader.

1447
00:52:19,470 --> 00:52:23,880
Now somewhat paradoxically,
when our pupils get bigger,

1448
00:52:23,880 --> 00:52:25,980
the pupils of our eyes that is,

1449
00:52:25,980 --> 00:52:27,840
our visual world actually narrows,

1450
00:52:27,840 --> 00:52:29,370
it becomes more tunnel-like.

1451
00:52:29,370 --> 00:52:30,300
A lot of people don't realize this.

1452
00:52:30,300 --> 00:52:32,480
When our pupils are really
small, that means we are relaxed.

1453
00:52:32,480 --> 00:52:33,360
So if you ever see someone

1454
00:52:33,360 --> 00:52:35,940
with really tiny or pin size pupils,

1455
00:52:35,940 --> 00:52:36,840
they're very relaxed.

1456
00:52:36,840 --> 00:52:39,270
If their pupils are very
big, they're very dilated,

1457
00:52:39,270 --> 00:52:42,000
well then they are very amped up,

1458
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:44,070
they are very, very alert.

1459
00:52:44,070 --> 00:52:47,400
Caffeine increases alertness
by increasing epinephrine,

1460
00:52:47,400 --> 00:52:50,907
adrenaline release both in
the brain and within the body.

1461
00:52:50,907 --> 00:52:53,190
And so that's another
way that it facilitates

1462
00:52:53,190 --> 00:52:55,244
focus and concentration.

1463
00:52:55,244 --> 00:52:58,110
Now there are other ways
to increase epinephrine

1464
00:52:58,110 --> 00:53:00,990
in the brain and body besides
caffeine or other stimulants,

1465
00:53:00,990 --> 00:53:02,880
and in fact, that has been studied.

1466
00:53:02,880 --> 00:53:04,050
There's an excellent study

1467
00:53:04,050 --> 00:53:08,100
that was carried out not that
long ago on how stress itself

1468
00:53:08,100 --> 00:53:11,190
can increase our ability
to focus and concentrate,

1469
00:53:11,190 --> 00:53:12,690
that's right how stress itself

1470
00:53:12,690 --> 00:53:14,580
can increase focus and concentration.

1471
00:53:14,580 --> 00:53:15,870
You know, most people think of stress

1472
00:53:15,870 --> 00:53:18,060
as impairing our ability to focus,

1473
00:53:18,060 --> 00:53:19,290
but that's actually not true.

1474
00:53:19,290 --> 00:53:22,230
When we are stressed, it
involves the deployment,

1475
00:53:22,230 --> 00:53:24,630
the release of adrenaline, epinephrine,

1476
00:53:24,630 --> 00:53:27,930
and that that adrenaline both
changes our visual field,

1477
00:53:27,930 --> 00:53:29,700
in other words, it narrows our vision

1478
00:53:29,700 --> 00:53:32,100
to a more tunnel-like focus,

1479
00:53:32,100 --> 00:53:33,990
that is it makes the arrow

1480
00:53:33,990 --> 00:53:37,410
in our metaphor of the arrow more sharp,

1481
00:53:37,410 --> 00:53:39,927
and it improves our concentration.

1482
00:53:39,927 --> 00:53:42,300
And this makes sense given
what we know about stress.

1483
00:53:42,300 --> 00:53:43,652
When we're stressed,

1484
00:53:43,652 --> 00:53:44,485
we tend to be stressed
about a specific thing,

1485
00:53:44,485 --> 00:53:46,800
we start anticipating
or wondering or thinking

1486
00:53:46,800 --> 00:53:47,850
about what's going to happen next?

1487
00:53:47,850 --> 00:53:48,810
What led up to this?

1488
00:53:48,810 --> 00:53:49,920
How is this going to impact me?

1489
00:53:49,920 --> 00:53:51,360
How do I feel right now?

1490
00:53:51,360 --> 00:53:53,160
It really narrows the context

1491
00:53:53,160 --> 00:53:55,140
of our thinking and our behavior.

1492
00:53:55,140 --> 00:53:57,120
So one of my favorite studies
that really illustrates

1493
00:53:57,120 --> 00:54:00,450
how stress can improve
concentration and performance

1494
00:54:00,450 --> 00:54:02,067
is one that was published
not that long ago

1495
00:54:02,067 --> 00:54:04,560
and I will provide a link
to this in the show notes.

1496
00:54:04,560 --> 00:54:05,880
It's a paper published

1497
00:54:05,880 --> 00:54:08,820
in the "Journal of Experimental
Psychology" in 2020.

1498
00:54:08,820 --> 00:54:11,017
The title of the paper
is, not surprisingly,

1499
00:54:11,017 --> 00:54:14,070
"Acute stress improves
concentration performance",

1500
00:54:14,070 --> 00:54:18,300
first author DeGroote, d-e-g-r-o-o-t-e.

1501
00:54:18,300 --> 00:54:21,240
And this study involved
taking a number of subjects

1502
00:54:21,240 --> 00:54:23,520
and stressing them out or not

1503
00:54:23,520 --> 00:54:27,000
prior to a cognitive
or concentration task.

1504
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:28,650
And there are a lot of data in this paper,

1505
00:54:28,650 --> 00:54:31,740
but I'm just going to hone in
on one specific set of data.

1506
00:54:31,740 --> 00:54:33,270
And I should mention as I go there,

1507
00:54:33,270 --> 00:54:35,820
that they measured things like
cortisol, a stress hormone,

1508
00:54:35,820 --> 00:54:38,850
they measured anxiety, it
was a quite thorough study.

1509
00:54:38,850 --> 00:54:42,000
And what they found was that
concentration performance

1510
00:54:42,000 --> 00:54:45,330
improved manyfold, I should say, from,

1511
00:54:45,330 --> 00:54:47,070
there was a greater than doubling

1512
00:54:47,070 --> 00:54:50,460
of concentration and
performance in the stress group.

1513
00:54:50,460 --> 00:54:52,620
And stress in this context was provided

1514
00:54:52,620 --> 00:54:55,200
using a standard way of inducing stress.

1515
00:54:55,200 --> 00:54:56,033
What they basically do

1516
00:54:56,033 --> 00:54:58,050
is they bring subjects into the laboratory

1517
00:54:58,050 --> 00:55:01,980
and they have to either do
something fairly mundane

1518
00:55:01,980 --> 00:55:03,150
in the control group

1519
00:55:03,150 --> 00:55:06,390
or they have to do a
simulated job interview,

1520
00:55:06,390 --> 00:55:07,560
an arithmetic task,

1521
00:55:07,560 --> 00:55:09,360
and they're being evaluated
as they're doing this.

1522
00:55:09,360 --> 00:55:12,420
So this isn't intense psychosocial stress.

1523
00:55:12,420 --> 00:55:14,160
They're not watching anything disturbing,

1524
00:55:14,160 --> 00:55:15,990
they're not being traumatized
in any kind of way.

1525
00:55:15,990 --> 00:55:18,390
This is fairly low levels of stress

1526
00:55:18,390 --> 00:55:20,670
that raised their levels of epinephrine,

1527
00:55:20,670 --> 00:55:22,560
and we know this from this study,

1528
00:55:22,560 --> 00:55:25,230
and their levels of cortisol,
another stress hormone,

1529
00:55:25,230 --> 00:55:28,230
modestly within their brain and blood.

1530
00:55:28,230 --> 00:55:31,350
But that even modest increase
in these stress hormones

1531
00:55:31,350 --> 00:55:34,590
and their reported
psychological levels of stress

1532
00:55:34,590 --> 00:55:37,186
really enhanced their
focus and concentration.

1533
00:55:37,186 --> 00:55:40,650
This may come as surprising
'cause like many people think,

1534
00:55:40,650 --> 00:55:42,810
gosh, stress really diminishes
cognitive performance,

1535
00:55:42,810 --> 00:55:44,070
but that's absolutely wrong,

1536
00:55:44,070 --> 00:55:46,470
stress improves cognitive performance.

1537
00:55:46,470 --> 00:55:49,350
Now of course there are other
ways to increase stress levels

1538
00:55:49,350 --> 00:55:50,580
and to do that in healthy ways

1539
00:55:50,580 --> 00:55:52,740
to improve concentration and performance

1540
00:55:52,740 --> 00:55:54,840
and one of the best ways to do that

1541
00:55:54,840 --> 00:55:58,050
because it's so sure fire
and it's generally safe

1542
00:55:58,050 --> 00:56:01,680
provided you do it safely
is deliberate cold exposure.

1543
00:56:01,680 --> 00:56:04,410
This is something I've talked
about on the podcast before,

1544
00:56:04,410 --> 00:56:06,270
but deliberate cold
exposure can be achieved

1545
00:56:06,270 --> 00:56:09,330
by getting into a cold shower
for one to five minutes.

1546
00:56:09,330 --> 00:56:10,200
If you're not used to it,

1547
00:56:10,200 --> 00:56:11,970
you probably want to
start with one minute,

1548
00:56:11,970 --> 00:56:13,710
or you can get into an ice bath,

1549
00:56:13,710 --> 00:56:15,030
and nowadays there are
a number of different

1550
00:56:15,030 --> 00:56:17,160
commercial sources of
circulating cold water

1551
00:56:17,160 --> 00:56:19,830
or if you have access
to a body of cold water

1552
00:56:19,830 --> 00:56:22,260
like a lake or a pool or an ocean.

1553
00:56:22,260 --> 00:56:26,310
We know that getting into
cold water or under cold water

1554
00:56:26,310 --> 00:56:30,210
greatly increases epinephrine
levels and dopamine levels

1555
00:56:30,210 --> 00:56:31,320
in the brain and blood.

1556
00:56:31,320 --> 00:56:32,910
There's a beautiful
study that was published

1557
00:56:32,910 --> 00:56:35,010
in the European Journal of Physiology

1558
00:56:35,010 --> 00:56:38,370
that showed that the increases
in dopamine are massive,

1559
00:56:38,370 --> 00:56:39,960
near doubling or more

1560
00:56:39,960 --> 00:56:42,960
of dopamine levels that are
very long lasting for hours,

1561
00:56:42,960 --> 00:56:46,110
and epinephrine, and
indeed cortisol levels

1562
00:56:46,110 --> 00:56:47,700
are also increased,

1563
00:56:47,700 --> 00:56:49,830
and in ways that support

1564
00:56:49,830 --> 00:56:53,607
not just immune system
function because they do that,

1565
00:56:53,607 --> 00:56:55,350
and mood because it does that,

1566
00:56:55,350 --> 00:56:57,990
but they can really improve
concentration and focus.

1567
00:56:57,990 --> 00:57:01,200
I touched on this a little
bit in an episode about memory

1568
00:57:01,200 --> 00:57:03,960
that there's an age old practice

1569
00:57:03,960 --> 00:57:06,030
really dating back to medieval times

1570
00:57:06,030 --> 00:57:08,550
of putting people into cold water

1571
00:57:08,550 --> 00:57:11,490
right after they learn
something in order to spike,

1572
00:57:11,490 --> 00:57:12,780
to increase their epinephrine

1573
00:57:12,780 --> 00:57:14,820
as a way to consolidate those memories.

1574
00:57:14,820 --> 00:57:16,380
For the sake of today's discussion,

1575
00:57:16,380 --> 00:57:17,400
if you are interested

1576
00:57:17,400 --> 00:57:20,190
in ways to improve
focus and concentration,

1577
00:57:20,190 --> 00:57:23,040
you need to increase your epinephrine,

1578
00:57:23,040 --> 00:57:24,930
your adrenaline levels.

1579
00:57:24,930 --> 00:57:26,373
Cold water exposure

1580
00:57:26,373 --> 00:57:29,538
is one of the most
efficient ways to do that.

1581
00:57:29,538 --> 00:57:31,620
This is not a biohack.

1582
00:57:31,620 --> 00:57:33,120
I don't like the word hack,

1583
00:57:33,120 --> 00:57:34,380
I know it's commonly used,

1584
00:57:34,380 --> 00:57:36,720
but a hack is something
where you're using one thing

1585
00:57:36,720 --> 00:57:38,880
for a different purpose than
it was originally intended for

1586
00:57:38,880 --> 00:57:39,960
and here, I'm not referring

1587
00:57:39,960 --> 00:57:41,040
to the shower or the cold bath,

1588
00:57:41,040 --> 00:57:42,510
I'm referring to epinephrine.

1589
00:57:42,510 --> 00:57:43,860
Epinephrine is a neurochemical

1590
00:57:43,860 --> 00:57:47,520
that will place your vision
into more of a tunnel mode,

1591
00:57:47,520 --> 00:57:48,540
which will allow you to focus

1592
00:57:48,540 --> 00:57:51,480
on cognitive work or physical
work in a more specific way,

1593
00:57:51,480 --> 00:57:53,070
you're not going to be as distractable,

1594
00:57:53,070 --> 00:57:55,020
and it's very easy to achieve

1595
00:57:55,020 --> 00:57:57,966
by getting into a cold shower
or a cold body of water

1596
00:57:57,966 --> 00:58:00,030
for a brief period of time.

1597
00:58:00,030 --> 00:58:04,770
People always ask how long to
get under or into cold water

1598
00:58:04,770 --> 00:58:05,940
and how cold to make it.

1599
00:58:05,940 --> 00:58:07,890
Here's the thing, it should
be uncomfortably cold,

1600
00:58:07,890 --> 00:58:10,860
but safe to stay in for
one to five minutes.

1601
00:58:10,860 --> 00:58:13,050
Okay so uncomfortably cold,
you really want to get out,

1602
00:58:13,050 --> 00:58:13,883
but safe to stay in,

1603
00:58:13,883 --> 00:58:15,900
not so cold that it's going
to give you a heart attack

1604
00:58:15,900 --> 00:58:17,670
and not so warm that it's comfortable

1605
00:58:17,670 --> 00:58:20,070
that it doesn't create
that adrenaline release.

1606
00:58:20,070 --> 00:58:21,240
Cold water exposure,

1607
00:58:21,240 --> 00:58:22,500
I should say deliberate, cold water

1608
00:58:22,500 --> 00:58:24,671
or non deliberate cold water exposure

1609
00:58:24,671 --> 00:58:28,050
reliably increases epinephrine levels.

1610
00:58:28,050 --> 00:58:31,230
It is incredibly useful
as a tool for this,

1611
00:58:31,230 --> 00:58:35,850
and it is in fact, zero cost
or even negative zero cost.

1612
00:58:35,850 --> 00:58:37,140
How could it be negative zero cost?

1613
00:58:37,140 --> 00:58:39,210
Well, you can certainly
save on your heating bill

1614
00:58:39,210 --> 00:58:41,610
by taking a cold shower so that's one way.

1615
00:58:41,610 --> 00:58:44,160
And for those of you that
have access to devices

1616
00:58:44,160 --> 00:58:46,140
or locations where you
can get into cold water,

1617
00:58:46,140 --> 00:58:47,130
you can submerge,

1618
00:58:47,130 --> 00:58:48,450
well then that can work.

1619
00:58:48,450 --> 00:58:50,848
For those of you that don't,
maybe you take a cold bath,

1620
00:58:50,848 --> 00:58:53,190
you get in up to your neck,
that's going to be most efficient.

1621
00:58:53,190 --> 00:58:54,660
For those of you that can't do that,

1622
00:58:54,660 --> 00:58:55,740
you'll get under a cold shower.

1623
00:58:55,740 --> 00:58:59,370
Again, it should be comfortably cold

1624
00:58:59,370 --> 00:59:00,810
to the point where you want to get out,

1625
00:59:00,810 --> 00:59:04,110
but that you can safely stay
in for one to five minutes.

1626
00:59:04,110 --> 00:59:06,030
How long should you do
it before a workout?

1627
00:59:06,030 --> 00:59:08,640
Well, if you get into really cold water,

1628
00:59:08,640 --> 00:59:09,600
it's uncomfortably cold

1629
00:59:09,600 --> 00:59:11,010
and get out after about three minutes,

1630
00:59:11,010 --> 00:59:13,990
you're probably good to go,
dry off and get to work.

1631
00:59:13,990 --> 00:59:16,500
Some of you might think
this is a little bit silly

1632
00:59:16,500 --> 00:59:18,540
as a tool for focus and concentration,

1633
00:59:18,540 --> 00:59:21,600
but if you look at the data on epinephrine

1634
00:59:21,600 --> 00:59:24,120
and how powerfully it can increase focus,

1635
00:59:24,120 --> 00:59:26,040
I think you'd be very impressed.

1636
00:59:26,040 --> 00:59:28,500
I mean it certainly can
increase one's ability

1637
00:59:28,500 --> 00:59:30,300
to attend to specific visual stimuli,

1638
00:59:30,300 --> 00:59:32,700
so for reading or math work, et cetera,

1639
00:59:32,700 --> 00:59:34,140
it's going to be very useful.

1640
00:59:34,140 --> 00:59:35,490
And of course you don't
want to make it so cold

1641
00:59:35,490 --> 00:59:37,800
that you're shivering and
chattering the whole time.

1642
00:59:37,800 --> 00:59:39,510
And of course you could, if you like,

1643
00:59:39,510 --> 00:59:41,310
combine this with 40 HZ binaural beats,

1644
00:59:41,310 --> 00:59:42,143
there's no reason

1645
00:59:42,143 --> 00:59:44,070
why you couldn't combine
the two protocols.

1646
00:59:44,070 --> 00:59:46,860
But the point here is that a
lot of people would love to

1647
00:59:46,860 --> 00:59:48,690
and I think ought to leverage

1648
00:59:48,690 --> 00:59:51,330
the health promoting and powerful effects

1649
00:59:51,330 --> 00:59:54,540
of increasing epinephrine
on focusing concentration

1650
00:59:54,540 --> 00:59:57,000
and running out and getting
stressed by a life event

1651
00:59:57,000 --> 00:59:59,190
or getting into an argument
or something like that

1652
00:59:59,190 --> 01:00:01,470
simply as a way to increase
focus and concentration

1653
01:00:01,470 --> 01:00:03,060
doesn't seem that adaptive to me.

1654
01:00:03,060 --> 01:00:04,290
So deliberate cold exposure

1655
01:00:04,290 --> 01:00:05,820
is a straightforward way to do that,

1656
01:00:05,820 --> 01:00:07,290
it doesn't involve anyone else,

1657
01:00:07,290 --> 01:00:08,610
I suppose you could do
it with somebody else,

1658
01:00:08,610 --> 01:00:10,260
but it doesn't require anyone else.

1659
01:00:10,260 --> 01:00:12,750
And again, there are zero low

1660
01:00:12,750 --> 01:00:14,970
and even negative cost
ways to approach that.

1661
01:00:14,970 --> 01:00:16,260
If you'd like to know how long

1662
01:00:16,260 --> 01:00:19,350
the positive effects of epinephrine last

1663
01:00:19,350 --> 01:00:21,570
toward improving focus and concentration,

1664
01:00:21,570 --> 01:00:23,520
well, if we look to that
study from DeGroote et al,

1665
01:00:23,520 --> 01:00:25,692
the acute stress improves
cognitive performance study,

1666
01:00:25,692 --> 01:00:28,770
they measured concentration before

1667
01:00:28,770 --> 01:00:31,895
and 30 minutes after
the stress was induced

1668
01:00:31,895 --> 01:00:34,770
and there does appear to
be a quite long lasting,

1669
01:00:34,770 --> 01:00:37,260
really up to an hour or more effect

1670
01:00:37,260 --> 01:00:39,420
of increasing epinephrine.

1671
01:00:39,420 --> 01:00:42,180
So how might you apply
these sorts of protocols

1672
01:00:42,180 --> 01:00:44,550
early in the day or later in the day?

1673
01:00:44,550 --> 01:00:47,790
Well, one suggestion or one
potential protocol would be

1674
01:00:47,790 --> 01:00:49,590
if you're going to sit
down and do some work,

1675
01:00:49,590 --> 01:00:51,390
if you're already feeling
alert and focused,

1676
01:00:51,390 --> 01:00:52,710
no need to reach to this tool,

1677
01:00:52,710 --> 01:00:55,110
but if you're feeling like
your focus and alertness

1678
01:00:55,110 --> 01:00:56,730
isn't quite where you'd like it to be,

1679
01:00:56,730 --> 01:00:59,010
you could take a three
minute very cold shower

1680
01:00:59,010 --> 01:01:01,050
or submerge yourself in cold
water for three minutes,

1681
01:01:01,050 --> 01:01:02,760
you might have a cup of coffee as well

1682
01:01:02,760 --> 01:01:04,050
and then sit down and do that work,

1683
01:01:04,050 --> 01:01:06,660
maybe even throw in the
40 HZ binaural beats.

1684
01:01:06,660 --> 01:01:09,780
All of that would be layering
in the different systems,

1685
01:01:09,780 --> 01:01:11,340
the different neurochemicals,

1686
01:01:11,340 --> 01:01:15,060
such as acetylcholine,
epinephrine and dopamine,

1687
01:01:15,060 --> 01:01:16,080
that are going to lend themselves

1688
01:01:16,080 --> 01:01:19,320
to a really terrific 90
minute or less work about.

1689
01:01:19,320 --> 01:01:22,170
Now I'd like to discuss some
of the purely behavioral tools

1690
01:01:22,170 --> 01:01:24,210
that quality peer reviewed science say

1691
01:01:24,210 --> 01:01:27,870
can improve focus and
concentration significantly.

1692
01:01:27,870 --> 01:01:29,730
At the beginning of today's episode,

1693
01:01:29,730 --> 01:01:32,430
I talked about the study
from Dr. Wendy Suzuki's lab

1694
01:01:32,430 --> 01:01:35,220
where they explored a 13 minute meditation

1695
01:01:35,220 --> 01:01:38,160
done every day for a
period of eight weeks.

1696
01:01:38,160 --> 01:01:40,650
That meditation led to
significant improvements

1697
01:01:40,650 --> 01:01:42,840
in focus and concentration ability,

1698
01:01:42,840 --> 01:01:45,480
as well as other aspects
of cognitive performance.

1699
01:01:45,480 --> 01:01:48,540
It also improved mood and reduced stress.

1700
01:01:48,540 --> 01:01:51,300
So you might be wondering what
exactly is this meditation?

1701
01:01:51,300 --> 01:01:52,950
The meditation is very simple

1702
01:01:52,950 --> 01:01:55,200
and it's one that anyone can perform.

1703
01:01:55,200 --> 01:01:57,390
What you would want to do is set a timer

1704
01:01:57,390 --> 01:01:58,860
for about 13 minutes,

1705
01:01:58,860 --> 01:02:00,810
I don't think it has to
be exactly 13 minutes,

1706
01:02:00,810 --> 01:02:02,986
but since that's what they
included in the study,

1707
01:02:02,986 --> 01:02:05,730
you would set a timer for 13 minutes.

1708
01:02:05,730 --> 01:02:09,120
You would sit or lie
down, close your eyes,

1709
01:02:09,120 --> 01:02:12,240
and you would simply
focus on your breathing.

1710
01:02:12,240 --> 01:02:13,500
Most people are going to benefit

1711
01:02:13,500 --> 01:02:15,900
from only doing that
breathing through their nose,

1712
01:02:15,900 --> 01:02:18,090
but if you have some sort of obstruction

1713
01:02:18,090 --> 01:02:19,710
or inability to breathe
just through your nose,

1714
01:02:19,710 --> 01:02:20,760
you could probably also do it

1715
01:02:20,760 --> 01:02:23,430
by breathing through your nose
and mouth or just your mouth.

1716
01:02:23,430 --> 01:02:25,890
But ideally you would
do just nasal breathing

1717
01:02:25,890 --> 01:02:27,180
for a period of 13 minutes,

1718
01:02:27,180 --> 01:02:28,860
concentrating on that breathing,

1719
01:02:28,860 --> 01:02:32,220
and concentrating, meaning
bringing your awareness,

1720
01:02:32,220 --> 01:02:34,410
your so-called interoceptive awareness

1721
01:02:34,410 --> 01:02:37,050
if you wanted to get
really technical about it,

1722
01:02:37,050 --> 01:02:38,760
your interoceptive awareness

1723
01:02:38,760 --> 01:02:42,240
to a point just about an
inch inside of your forehead.

1724
01:02:42,240 --> 01:02:43,073
Now, of course,

1725
01:02:43,073 --> 01:02:44,954
that might sound kind
of gory to some of you,

1726
01:02:44,954 --> 01:02:47,880
you've never actually
been inside your forehead,

1727
01:02:47,880 --> 01:02:50,220
but just about an inch
behind your forehead

1728
01:02:50,220 --> 01:02:52,350
is where you would want to
place your concentration

1729
01:02:52,350 --> 01:02:54,810
while also concentrating
on your breathing.

1730
01:02:54,810 --> 01:02:56,970
Now here's the thing about meditation

1731
01:02:56,970 --> 01:02:59,820
that all studies of meditation show,

1732
01:02:59,820 --> 01:03:04,080
which is that unless you are
a very experienced meditator,

1733
01:03:04,080 --> 01:03:06,030
your concentration, your focus

1734
01:03:06,030 --> 01:03:08,760
will drift away from your breathing

1735
01:03:08,760 --> 01:03:13,200
and away from that location
about an inch inside your head,

1736
01:03:13,200 --> 01:03:17,011
inside your brain, about
just behind your forehead.

1737
01:03:17,011 --> 01:03:20,940
That will happen maybe every
10 seconds, every 20 seconds,

1738
01:03:20,940 --> 01:03:22,650
maybe even every five seconds,

1739
01:03:22,650 --> 01:03:25,680
but an important part of
such a meditation practice

1740
01:03:25,680 --> 01:03:27,630
to improve concentration and focus

1741
01:03:27,630 --> 01:03:30,775
is that you are continually refocusing

1742
01:03:30,775 --> 01:03:32,700
back to that specific location

1743
01:03:32,700 --> 01:03:35,115
and refocusing back on your breath.

1744
01:03:35,115 --> 01:03:37,920
This is something that again,
is not often discussed.

1745
01:03:37,920 --> 01:03:39,540
People think that if you do a meditation

1746
01:03:39,540 --> 01:03:41,400
and you're supposed to
concentrate on your breath,

1747
01:03:41,400 --> 01:03:42,450
that if your mind drifts

1748
01:03:42,450 --> 01:03:44,340
that somehow you failed
in that meditation,

1749
01:03:44,340 --> 01:03:46,170
but actually that's not the case.

1750
01:03:46,170 --> 01:03:49,650
A huge component of improving your ability

1751
01:03:49,650 --> 01:03:52,740
to focus and concentrate
by way of neuroplasticity,

1752
01:03:52,740 --> 01:03:55,860
rewiring of the circuits
for focus and concentration,

1753
01:03:55,860 --> 01:03:59,520
is the repeated return to a state of focus

1754
01:03:59,520 --> 01:04:03,210
from a state of non-focus
or diminished focus.

1755
01:04:03,210 --> 01:04:06,239
So think about it like trying
to drive down the freeway

1756
01:04:06,239 --> 01:04:09,510
and staying between the
lane lines, excuse me.

1757
01:04:09,510 --> 01:04:10,590
And every once in a while,

1758
01:04:10,590 --> 01:04:13,050
because there's a bit
of drift on the vehicle,

1759
01:04:13,050 --> 01:04:14,490
maybe the wheels aren't aligned correctly

1760
01:04:14,490 --> 01:04:16,320
or there's something else
wrong with the chassis

1761
01:04:16,320 --> 01:04:17,340
or the steering device,

1762
01:04:17,340 --> 01:04:19,080
it starts to drift right a little bit,

1763
01:04:19,080 --> 01:04:20,670
then you hit the rumble strip to go rrrr,

1764
01:04:20,670 --> 01:04:22,380
and then you pull back to the center.

1765
01:04:22,380 --> 01:04:25,890
That's really what a focused
meditation practice is about

1766
01:04:25,890 --> 01:04:28,350
as opposed to expecting yourself

1767
01:04:28,350 --> 01:04:31,350
to stay between the mental
lane lines, so to speak.

1768
01:04:31,350 --> 01:04:33,450
So if you're somebody who's
going to do a practice

1769
01:04:33,450 --> 01:04:34,770
of the sort that I described,

1770
01:04:34,770 --> 01:04:37,350
13 minute meditation practice every day,

1771
01:04:37,350 --> 01:04:39,360
you'd want to sit or lie
down, close your eyes,

1772
01:04:39,360 --> 01:04:40,740
start to concentrate on your breath,

1773
01:04:40,740 --> 01:04:42,300
focus your attention

1774
01:04:42,300 --> 01:04:45,270
on a location about an
inch behind your forehead,

1775
01:04:45,270 --> 01:04:48,120
and then fully expect that at some point,

1776
01:04:48,120 --> 01:04:49,830
you'll be thinking about something else,

1777
01:04:49,830 --> 01:04:52,830
and that's a cue to focus
back to that location

1778
01:04:52,830 --> 01:04:54,270
just about an inch behind your forehead

1779
01:04:54,270 --> 01:04:56,220
and back to your breath.

1780
01:04:56,220 --> 01:04:57,780
By doing that repeatedly over and over,

1781
01:04:57,780 --> 01:04:59,400
what you're really training up

1782
01:04:59,400 --> 01:05:02,160
is the network within your brain

1783
01:05:02,160 --> 01:05:04,560
that indeed includes
that prefrontal cortex

1784
01:05:04,560 --> 01:05:06,600
that you're focusing on as
well as some other structures,

1785
01:05:06,600 --> 01:05:09,240
the inferior temporal cortex,
indeed the hippocampus,

1786
01:05:09,240 --> 01:05:10,890
a structure associated with memory,

1787
01:05:10,890 --> 01:05:13,230
and other components of the neural circuit

1788
01:05:13,230 --> 01:05:14,880
that are involved in directing

1789
01:05:14,880 --> 01:05:17,100
our mental focus and concentration.

1790
01:05:17,100 --> 01:05:19,440
Again, I can't emphasize the importance

1791
01:05:19,440 --> 01:05:22,890
of this practice being one
of focusing and refocusing.

1792
01:05:22,890 --> 01:05:25,170
In fact, I would prefer
to call such a practice,

1793
01:05:25,170 --> 01:05:29,610
a refocus focused meditation,
or a constantly refocusing,

1794
01:05:29,610 --> 01:05:31,950
or maybe you all can come up
with a better name for it,

1795
01:05:31,950 --> 01:05:33,870
I'm certainly not that
good at naming things,

1796
01:05:33,870 --> 01:05:36,030
but this sort of meditation practice

1797
01:05:36,030 --> 01:05:36,863
has been shown

1798
01:05:36,863 --> 01:05:39,727
in the study by the Suzuki
lab and other studies

1799
01:05:39,727 --> 01:05:42,720
to really improve people's ability

1800
01:05:42,720 --> 01:05:45,300
to focus and remain focused,

1801
01:05:45,300 --> 01:05:49,140
so much so that in the beautiful
book, "Altered States,"

1802
01:05:49,140 --> 01:05:51,450
they describe a number of
different meditation practices,

1803
01:05:51,450 --> 01:05:54,750
some a little bit longer than
the one that I described,

1804
01:05:54,750 --> 01:05:57,030
one that's 17 minutes,
another one that's 30 minutes,

1805
01:05:57,030 --> 01:05:59,010
some people will meditate
as long as 60 minutes a day,

1806
01:05:59,010 --> 01:06:01,080
although that's quite a
long time, in my opinion.

1807
01:06:01,080 --> 01:06:03,840
The point here isn't how long you focus

1808
01:06:03,840 --> 01:06:06,870
or somehow trying to achieve total focus

1809
01:06:06,870 --> 01:06:09,720
for the entire 13 minute or 17 minute

1810
01:06:09,720 --> 01:06:12,390
or 60 minute about of meditation.

1811
01:06:12,390 --> 01:06:13,740
While that would be wonderful

1812
01:06:13,740 --> 01:06:15,810
and I think many people aspire to do that,

1813
01:06:15,810 --> 01:06:17,310
that's a lot of hard mental work.

1814
01:06:17,310 --> 01:06:19,710
I think for most people out
there, including myself,

1815
01:06:19,710 --> 01:06:24,180
a relatively short meditation
practice of about 13 minutes

1816
01:06:24,180 --> 01:06:26,401
in which you fully expect

1817
01:06:26,401 --> 01:06:28,740
your focus and concentration to drift,

1818
01:06:28,740 --> 01:06:30,630
but that you are continually refocusing

1819
01:06:30,630 --> 01:06:32,520
is going to be the most effective,

1820
01:06:32,520 --> 01:06:34,320
yes, indeed, the most effective

1821
01:06:34,320 --> 01:06:37,740
at teaching yourself to
focus and stay concentrated.

1822
01:06:37,740 --> 01:06:39,630
In fact, I invite you to interpret

1823
01:06:39,630 --> 01:06:42,930
every time that you
focus off that location

1824
01:06:42,930 --> 01:06:44,850
about one inch behind your forehead,

1825
01:06:44,850 --> 01:06:46,350
as an opportunity to refocus

1826
01:06:46,350 --> 01:06:49,290
and think about the
refocusing as the trigger

1827
01:06:49,290 --> 01:06:51,000
for teaching your neural circuits

1828
01:06:51,000 --> 01:06:53,610
how to focus for extended periods of time.

1829
01:06:53,610 --> 01:06:55,773
And as a bonus to that sort
of meditation practice,

1830
01:06:55,773 --> 01:06:57,930
the study from Wendy Suzuki's lab

1831
01:06:57,930 --> 01:07:01,140
also showed that people
experience improvements in sleep

1832
01:07:01,140 --> 01:07:02,580
and improvements in memory,

1833
01:07:02,580 --> 01:07:05,040
so not just improvements in
mood and reduction in stress

1834
01:07:05,040 --> 01:07:07,440
and improvements in
focus and concentration,

1835
01:07:07,440 --> 01:07:09,120
but all these other positive benefits

1836
01:07:09,120 --> 01:07:12,240
from just doing that 13 minute
a day meditation practice.

1837
01:07:12,240 --> 01:07:14,070
It's one that I've started to adopt

1838
01:07:14,070 --> 01:07:15,477
and have felt tremendous benefit from

1839
01:07:15,477 --> 01:07:18,180
and that I encourage many
of you to try as well.

1840
01:07:18,180 --> 01:07:19,260
The one cautionary note

1841
01:07:19,260 --> 01:07:21,180
is the one that I mentioned at
the beginning of the episode,

1842
01:07:21,180 --> 01:07:25,950
which is because the refocus
as I'll call it, meditation,

1843
01:07:25,950 --> 01:07:28,500
does involve a significant
amount of effort

1844
01:07:28,500 --> 01:07:31,080
and engagement of these
prefrontal cortical circuits,

1845
01:07:31,080 --> 01:07:35,040
it is disruptive to sleep if
performed too closely to sleep.

1846
01:07:35,040 --> 01:07:36,660
So if you are going to do that practice,

1847
01:07:36,660 --> 01:07:38,400
I recommend that you not do it

1848
01:07:38,400 --> 01:07:40,800
within the four hours
prior to your bedtime.

1849
01:07:40,800 --> 01:07:41,633
Earlier I mentioned

1850
01:07:41,633 --> 01:07:43,682
that I would talk about
ways to improve focus

1851
01:07:43,682 --> 01:07:45,450
if you are sleep deprived.

1852
01:07:45,450 --> 01:07:47,760
This is something that
I'm all too familiar with.

1853
01:07:47,760 --> 01:07:50,250
I put a lot of effort
into optimizing my sleep,

1854
01:07:50,250 --> 01:07:51,840
that's something that
with each passing year,

1855
01:07:51,840 --> 01:07:53,370
I put more and more effort into,

1856
01:07:53,370 --> 01:07:54,930
again, because sleep is so vital

1857
01:07:54,930 --> 01:07:56,310
for mental health, physical health

1858
01:07:56,310 --> 01:07:58,080
and performance of all kinds,

1859
01:07:58,080 --> 01:08:00,840
but certainly in my role as a student,

1860
01:08:00,840 --> 01:08:03,930
in my role as a professor
and in my role in life,

1861
01:08:03,930 --> 01:08:05,850
I've had numerous times

1862
01:08:05,850 --> 01:08:07,920
in which I simply did not get enough sleep

1863
01:08:07,920 --> 01:08:10,980
or my sleep was terrible
for whatever reason,

1864
01:08:10,980 --> 01:08:13,530
and yet I still had work
demands and social demands,

1865
01:08:13,530 --> 01:08:14,363
et cetera.

1866
01:08:15,300 --> 01:08:17,069
One practice that is very effective

1867
01:08:17,069 --> 01:08:18,779
at allowing you to focus

1868
01:08:18,779 --> 01:08:20,969
better than you would otherwise

1869
01:08:20,970 --> 01:08:23,010
under conditions of sleep deprivation

1870
01:08:23,010 --> 01:08:26,279
is so called non-sleep deep rest or NSDR.

1871
01:08:26,279 --> 01:08:29,099
This is also referred to
sometimes as yoga nidra.

1872
01:08:29,100 --> 01:08:31,109
Yoga nidra actually means yoga sleep.

1873
01:08:31,109 --> 01:08:35,189
Yoga nidra is a practice of
lying down for about 10 to 30

1874
01:08:35,189 --> 01:08:37,259
sometimes even as long as 60 minutes,

1875
01:08:37,260 --> 01:08:39,720
you listen to a script,
it's an audio script,

1876
01:08:39,720 --> 01:08:42,390
that takes you through a
progressive deep relaxation,

1877
01:08:42,390 --> 01:08:43,770
it involves a body scan,

1878
01:08:43,770 --> 01:08:45,240
some long exhale breathing.

1879
01:08:45,240 --> 01:08:48,600
It is very restorative in the
sense that one tends to emerge

1880
01:08:48,600 --> 01:08:51,620
from yoga nidra or NSDR
feeling greatly refreshed

1881
01:08:51,620 --> 01:08:54,899
compared to how you felt prior to it.

1882
01:08:54,899 --> 01:08:57,269
There is also terrific neuroimaging data

